english:
  title: Edict Upon the Enthronement of the Queen Dowager
  author: Choe Yugyeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant has heard that those of supreme virtue enjoy blessings in abundance, and those of utmost filial devotion hold the honoring of parents as paramount. Thus do we exhaust the riches of the nine provinces to ensure her sustenance, and gather the finest beauty under heaven to bestow her titles—not merely to shine in this present age, but to serve as an exemplar for generations to come.

    With reverence, I consider our Sacred Mother: born with the gentle nature of the earth itself, graced with beauty like the crescent moon. Early did she take her rightful place in the Palace of Long Autumn, becoming consort to the former king. In her quiet virtue, she follows the teachings of the ancient poems, conducting herself through propriety; in her harmonious wisdom, she embodies the praises of the worthy. She possesses the humble diligence of the Ge Tang, yet harbors none of the petty attachments of Que Er. Her virtuous influence pervades the six palaces, her transformative power reaches across the four seas. Though Tu Shan's way once aided the Xia, and Hexi's devotion steadied the Liu house, our Sacred Mother's noble achievements and sublime conduct stand alone in their splendor.

    Reflecting upon my humble self: I have received the grace of her nurturing care. I have inherited the accumulated foundations of generations, yet feel the weight of this solemn trust. Rising early and retiring late, I tremble lest I diminish the legacy she has entrusted to me. With generous care for those below and the pacification of all people, I rely ever upon her sage instruction. We have brought order to the realm and harmony between heaven and earth—yet what merit belongs to this unworthy child? All blessings flow from our Sacred Mother's protecting grace. To inquire after her health and attend to her sustenance falls short of expressing true devotion. Only by glorifying her name and repaying her merit can we fulfill our filial duty.

    Following the great principles of the Spring and Autumn Annals and modeling ourselves upon the noble ceremonies of the Qin and Han dynasties, we have chosen an auspicious day and heeded the wishes of our ministers. With utmost respect, we hereby send our officials to present the jade tablet and golden seals, conferring upon her the exalted title of Queen Dowager. We humbly pray that she will receive these honors with joy and grace. May her sacred virtue and goodness extend through ten thousand ages, and may her abundant blessings endure as long as heaven and earth themselves.
  footnotes:
    - This is a ceremonial edict conferring the title of Queen Dowager upon the author's mother, written in the formal court language of medieval Korea.
    - References to 'Ge Tang' and 'Que Er' allude to classical poems celebrating female virtue and filial duty from the Book of Poetry.
    - Tu Shan and Hexi are legendary virtuous consorts from ancient Chinese history, invoked here as precedents for the Queen Dowager's excellence.
